Problem 1. Download the horse colic data set under Modules on Canvas. The data set measures different variables for horses with lesions in the digestive tract.

i. Split the data set into a training set and a test set. Fit a classification tree on the training set with only pulse and total.protein as predictors. Provide a plot of the classification tree.

import pandas as pd

# Load the data
data = pd.read_csv('/Users/aidanashrafi/Downloads/horse-colic.csv')

# Select specific columns (columns 4 to 6, 16, 19, 20, 22, 23 in 1-based R index)
# Equivalent to 3, 4, 5, 15, 18, 19, 21, 22 in Python 0-based index
data = data.iloc[:, [3, 4, 5, 15, 18, 19, 21, 22]]

# Number of columns to process (excluding the 'outcome' column)
p = 7

# Impute missing values for the first p columns with the column mean
for j in range(p):  # Loop through columns 0 to 6 (first 7 columns)
    data.iloc[:, j].fillna(data.iloc[:, j].mean(), inplace=True)

# Remove rows where 'outcome' (the last column) is still missing
data = data[data.iloc[:, -1].notna()]

# Check non-null
data.info()

import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier, plot_tree
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix, accuracy_score

# Split the data into training and testing sets
train, test = train_test_split(data, test_size=0.2, random_state=0)

# Prepare the training data (using 'pulse' and 'total.protein' as predictors)
X_train = train[['pulse', 'total protein']]
y_train = train['outcome']
X_test = test[['pulse', 'total protein']]
y_test = test['outcome']

# Fit a Decision Tree model (used specific parameters that were in code from class)
model = DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=30, min_samples_split=20, min_samples_leaf=7, random_state=0, ccp_alpha=0.01)
tree = model.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Plot the classification tree
plt.figure(figsize=(20, 10))
plot_tree(tree, feature_names=['pulse', 'total protein'], class_names=model.classes_.astype(str), filled=True)
plt.show()

How many internal nodes, leaves and branches does it have? What form do the decision boundaries have for this classification tree? Calculate the confusion matrix and the misclassification rate on the test set.

iii. Perform cost-complexity pruning on the classification tree in the previous part. Provide a plot of the pruned classification tree. How many internal nodes, leaves and branches are left? Which predictors appear to be most important for the classification of the outcome? Calculate the confusion matrix and the misclassification rate on the test set. How does this pruned classification tree compare against that in the previous part?

In [359]:
from sklearn.model_selection import KFold, GridSearchCV
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier, plot_tree
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Obtain the cost-complexity pruning path from the fitted model
ccp_path = full_tree.cost_complexity_pruning_path(X_train_all, y_train_all)
ccp_alphas = ccp_path.ccp_alphas  # Effective alphas

# Set up KFold cross-validation
kfold = KFold(10, shuffle=True, random_state=0)

# Use GridSearchCV to find the best alpha for pruning with an unfitted DecisionTreeClassifier
grid = GridSearchCV(full_tree, param_grid={'ccp_alpha': ccp_alphas},scoring='accuracy',refit=True,cv=kfold)

# Fit the GridSearchCV on the training data to find the best ccp_alpha
pruned = grid.fit(X_train_all, y_train_all)

# Get the best pruned tree from GridSearchCV
pruned_tree = pruned.best_estimator_

# Plot the pruned classification tree
plt.figure(figsize=(20, 10))
plot_tree(pruned_tree, feature_names=X_train_all.columns, class_names=pruned_tree.classes_.astype(str), filled=True, impurity=False)
plt.show()

from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix, accuracy_score

# Define the number of features (p)
p = X_train_all.shape[1]  # Number of predictors

# Initialize the Random Forest model
model = RandomForestClassifier(max_features=p, random_state=0)

# Fit the model on the training set
forest = model.fit(X_train_all, y_train_all)

# Get and plot the feature importances
importance = np.sort(forest.feature_importances_)

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
plt.barh(X_train_all.columns, importance)
plt.xlabel('Relative Importance')
plt.ylabel('Predictor')
plt.title('Predictor Importance for Random Forest Classifier')
plt.show()

import numpy as np 
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt 
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.svm import SVC 
from ISLP.svm import plot as plot_svm 

# Filter data to only include 'alive' and 'dead' outcomes (1 and 2)
filtered_data = data[data['outcome'].isin([1, 2])]
X_svc = filtered_data[['pulse', 'total protein']]
y_svc = filtered_data['outcome']

# Map outcome to binary (1 for 'lived', 0 for 'died')
y_encoded = y_svc.map({1: 1, 2: 0})

# Split the data into training and testing sets
X_train_svc, X_test_svc, y_train_svc, y_test_svc = train_test_split(X_svc, y_encoded, test_size=0.2, random_state=0)

# Reset indices to ensure alignment
X_train_svc = X_train_svc.reset_index(drop=True)
y_train_svc = y_train_svc.reset_index(drop=True)
X_test_svc = X_test_svc.reset_index(drop=True)
y_test_svc = y_test_svc.reset_index(drop=True)

# Fit the SVC model
svc_model = SVC(C=0.01, kernel="linear", random_state=0)
svc_fit = svc_model.fit(X_train_svc, y_train_svc)

# Ensure that X passed to plot_svm has valid feature names
plot_svm(X_train_svc, y_train_svc, svc_fit)
plt.show()
